      "code": "This is a BFS problem where state = current depth.\n\n- Start: depth n\n- From depth x: can jump to depths x-a[x], x-a[x]+1, ..., x-1, x (i.e., depth x-k for k=0..a[x])\n  - If x-k <= 0: escaped! (depth 0 or above ground)\n  - Otherwise: lands at depth (x-k) + b[x-k]\n- We want minimum number of jumps\n\nBFS with states being actual depths after slipping. The \"jump position\" before slipping is what we record in the path.\n\nFor BFS efficiency: from position x, we can reach any position in range [x - a[x], x]. After slipping, we end at pos + b[pos]. \n\nThe key challenge: from position x, we can jump to any of a[x]+1 positions. Naively this is O(n) per state, giving O(n^2) total which for n=300,000 might be too slow.\n\nWe need a smarter approach. We can use BFS with a \"range marking\" technique - when we process position x, we want to mark all positions in [x-a[x], x-1] as reachable (those that haven't been visited). We can use a set of unvisited nodes and iterate only through unvisited ones in the range.\n\nThis is the standard BFS with interval optimization using a sorted set of unvisited nodes.\n\nLet me implement this:\n- Keep a sorted structure of unvisited depths\n- For each depth x in BFS queue, find all unvisited depths in [x-a[x], x-1]\n- For each such depth y: if y <= 0, we found escape; else new_depth = y + b[y], if not visited, add to queue\n\nAlso handle the case where x itself is jumped to (jump 0 meters) - that just means staying, which is pointless unless we want to stay. Actually jumping 0 meters means depth stays same - that's a wasted jump, never optimal.\n\nLet me use a sorted list (or a simple approach with a pointer-based structure). I'll use a sorted container - in Python, I can use `SortedList` from `sortedcontainers`, but let me use a different approach with a `set` and iterate carefully, or use a segment-tree-like structure.\n\nActually for Python with n=300,000, I'll use the \"unvisited set\" approach with a sorted list. Let me use `sortedcontainers.SortedList`.\n\nSince we can't guarantee sortedcontainers is available, let me use a different approach: maintain an array and use a \"next unvisited\" pointer structure (like a union-find / disjoint set for next available).\n\nI'll implement a \"next unvisited\" structure where `next[i]` gives the smallest unvisited index >= i.\n\nFor each position x, I need unvisited positions in [x-a[x], x-1] (those that are >= x-a[x] and < x). I iterate using next[] starting from x-a[x], processing until next[i] >= x.\n\nAfter visiting position i, set next[i] = next[i+1] (path compression).\n\nThis gives nearly O(n) total work.\n\nLet me implement BFS with this structure, tracking parent for path reconstruction.",
